abstract: In a new survey, he’s second in South Carolina and tied for third in Nevada.
snippet: In a new survey, he’s second in South Carolina and tied for third in Nevada.
lead_paragraph: There hasn’t been much public polling in the Democratic primary race, and it hasn’t offered too many surprises even on the few occasions when it has materialized. Until Thursday night.

abstract: Ms. Warren is figuring out what candidates like Beto O’Rourke, Kamala Harris and Kirsten Gillibrand have already learned: It’s hard to appeal to both the center and the left of the Democratic Party.
snippet: Ms. Warren is figuring out what candidates like Beto O’Rourke, Kamala Harris and Kirsten Gillibrand have already learned: It’s hard to appeal to both the center and the left of the Democratic Party.
lead_paragraph: DAVENPORT, Iowa — The voter asked Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts the question on many Iowans’ minds: What did she have to offer besides her litany of policy proposals?

abstract: Nearly two months after his unusually late entry into the presidential race, the former Massachusetts governor has failed to draw big headlines or crucial endorsements. But he still has a long-shot plan.
snippet: Nearly two months after his unusually late entry into the presidential race, the former Massachusetts governor has failed to draw big headlines or crucial endorsements. But he still has a long-shot plan.
lead_paragraph: MANCHESTER, N.H. — Deval Patrick was eyeing the mug of bacon, the signature menu item at the Red Arrow Diner, a greasy spoon across the street from his presidential campaign’s new state headquarters.

abstract: Why Amy Klobuchar still has a chance.
snippet: Why Amy Klobuchar still has a chance.
lead_paragraph: If you’re like a lot of Democrats, you worry that Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren are too liberal — or at least that other voters think so. You’re also not buying the Pete Buttigieg hype. And you get nervous every time Joe Biden opens his mouth.
